      <h2>Why This Site Exists</h2>
      <p>In 1948, more than 700,000 Palestinians were displaced from their homes. Four hundred villages were destroyed. A refugee crisis began that now enters its eighth decade. The modern state of Israel was born. These events reshaped the Middle East — and the world is still living with the consequences.</p>
      <p>And yet, most people cannot explain what actually happened in 1948. They've heard fragments. They know the names of some of the wars. But the sequence, the scale, the human reality of that year remains unknown to most.</p>
      <p>This gap — between awareness and understanding — is where misinformation thrives. It's where myths propagate. It's where people who sincerely want to understand the Israeli-Palestinian conflict get lost.</p>
      <p>We built this site to close that gap.</p>

      <hr />

      <h2>What We Are</h2>
      <p>We are a documentation project. Our job is to collect, verify, and present evidence about what happened in 1948 — and what has happened since as a consequence of that year.</p>
      <p>We are not an advocacy organization. We do not tell you what to think, what to support, or what to oppose. We present documents, demographic data, historical maps, survivor testimonies, and legal rulings — and we let the evidence speak for itself.</p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Our Editorial Principle</h2>
      <blockquote>
        <p><strong>We don't argue. We document.</strong></p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Every factual claim on this site is footnoted with its source. Where sources conflict, we present both and explain the disagreement. Where the evidence is uncertain, we say so. We correct errors promptly and publicly. We do not use anonymous sources. We do not rely on partisan outlets.</p>
      <p>Our tone is journalistic — grounded, measured, precise. We write for skeptical readers who need to see the evidence before they trust the narrative. We do not mock, sneer, or condescend. We treat our readers as partners in understanding, not targets for conversion.</p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Sources & Methodology</h2>
      <p>This site draws primarily on the following categories of sources:</p>
      <ol style="margin-bottom:var(--space-lg);padding-left:var(--space-xl);">
        <li style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);"><strong>Primary documents:</strong> UN resolutions, British Mandate records, Israeli state archives, Red Cross reports, contemporaneous journalism.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);"><strong>Academic research:</strong> Peer-reviewed works by historians including Benny Morris, Ilan Pappé, Avi Shlaim, Rashid Khalidi, Walid Khalidi, and others — including scholars who disagree with each other.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);"><strong>Human rights reports:</strong> Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, B'Tselem, and other organizations with established credibility and verifiable methodology.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom:var(--space-sm);"><strong>Legal rulings:</strong> International Court of Justice advisory opinions, UN Security Council resolutions, and relevant international law.</li>
        <li><strong>Demographic data:</strong> British Mandate census records, Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics, UNRWA, and peer-reviewed demographic studies.</li>
      </ol>

      <hr />

      <h2>Corrections</h2>
      <p>We are committed to accuracy. If you find an error — a misstated fact, a broken citation, a missing source — please tell us. We will investigate and, if confirmed, correct the error publicly. This is not a promise of perfection. It is a promise of accountability.</p>

      <hr />

      <h2>A Note on Language</h2>
      <p>Words matter. We use "Nakba" (catastrophe) because that is the term Palestinians use to describe what happened to them. We use "occupation" because that is the term used by the International Court of Justice, the UN Security Council, and international humanitarian law. We use "apartheid" when citing organizations that have explicitly applied the legal definition of that crime — including Israeli and international human rights organizations.</p>
      <p>We do not use these terms as rhetoric. We use them because they have specific legal and historical meanings, and because avoiding them would be dishonest.</p>

    </div>
